<bibRefCitation author="Brusina" box="[513,667,281,308]" firstAuthor="Brusina" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 43" refId="ref6173" refString="BRUSINA S. 1897. - Materiaux pour la faune malacologique neogene de la Dalmatie, de la Croatie et de la Slavonie avec des especes de la Bosnie, de l'Herzegovine et de la Serbie. Djela Jugoslavenske Akademije Znanosti i Umjetnosti 18: i-xxi, 1 - 43." type="book chapter" year="1897">Brusina, 1897</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, currently considered a separate genus of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1865" box="[571,708,313,339]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Hydrobiidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Harzhauser" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Harzhauser" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 53" refId="ref6847" refString="HARZHAUSER M., NEUBAUER T. A., GEORGOPOULOU E., ESU D., D'AMICO C., PAVIA G., GIUNTELLI P. &amp; CARNEVALE G. 2015. - Late Messinian continental and Lago-Mare gastropods from the Tertiary Piedmont Basin, NW Italy. Bollettino della Societa Paleontologica Italiana 54: 1 - 53. https: // doi. org / 10.4435 / BSPI. 2015.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Harzhauser 
<emphasis box="[221,274,345,371]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="MolluscaBase" box="[352,580,345,371]" firstAuthor="MolluscaBase" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" refId="ref7497" refString="MOLLUSCABASE 2018 b. - Staja Brusina, 1897 †. Accessed through: World Register of Marine Species at: http: // www. marinespecies. org / aphia. php rp = taxdetails &amp; id = 820431 on 2018 - 05 - 03" type="url" year="2018" yearSuffix="b">MolluscaBase 2018b</bibRefCitation>
). Examination of further material allowed distinguishing this species from 
<emphasis box="[717,768,377,403]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Staja</emphasis>
, which is a Miocene Eastern European taxon rich in several species (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="MolluscaBase" box="[247,463,440,466]" firstAuthor="MolluscaBase" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" refId="ref7497" refString="MOLLUSCABASE 2018 b. - Staja Brusina, 1897 †. Accessed through: World Register of Marine Species at: http: // www. marinespecies. org / aphia. php rp = taxdetails &amp; id = 820431 on 2018 - 05 - 03" type="url" year="2018" yearSuffix="b">MolluscaBase 2018b</bibRefCitation>
), characterised by a very small size (dimensional range: H = 
<quantity box="[454,589,472,499]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="2.05" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="1.6">1.6-2.5 mm</quantity>
, W = 
<quantity box="[655,767,472,499]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="1.1" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.0">1-1.2 mm</quantity>
) and a mainly conical shell with regularly growing whorls (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Brusina" box="[132,282,536,562]" firstAuthor="Brusina" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 43" refId="ref6173" refString="BRUSINA S. 1897. - Materiaux pour la faune malacologique neogene de la Dalmatie, de la Croatie et de la Slavonie avec des especes de la Bosnie, de l'Herzegovine et de la Serbie. Djela Jugoslavenske Akademije Znanosti i Umjetnosti 18: i-xxi, 1 - 43." type="book chapter" year="1897">Brusina 1897</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jekelius" box="[297,446,536,562]" firstAuthor="Jekelius" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 167" refId="ref7089" refString="JEKELIUS E. 1944. - Sarmat und Pont von Soceni. Memoriile Institutului Geologic al Romaniei 5: 1 - 167." type="journal article" year="1944">Jekelius 1944</bibRefCitation>
). The assignment of 
<emphasis box="[681,745,537,562]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">ionica</emphasis>
n. sp. to the same genus as 
<emphasis box="[388,512,568,594]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">galatoniana</emphasis>
n. sp. is likely supported by similar conchological characters between the two species, such as hydrobioid shell shape with slightly convex whorls, last whorl higher, ovate-elongate and barely flared aperture, and smooth protoconch. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann" authorityYear="1821" box="[410,510,695,721]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Hydrobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[410,510,695,721]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Hydrobia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(s.l.) 
<emphasis box="[571,635,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">ionica</emphasis>
n. sp. differs from 
<emphasis box="[195,224,728,753]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">H.</emphasis>
(s.l.) 
<emphasis box="[290,415,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">galatoniana</emphasis>
n. sp. in having a more globose shell, a wider apical angle, a smaller protoconch, the last whorl proportionally wider and higher, the aperture more elongate, and a smaller H/W (max) ratio (1.8 vs 2.08). It differs from the coeval 
<emphasis box="[388,671,855,881]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">H. dubuissonii hydruntina</emphasis>
from the Upper Oligocene marls of Otranto bauxite quarry (
<bibRefCitation author="Esu &amp; Girotti" firstAuthor="Esu" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" pagination="137 - 174" refId="ref6441" refString="ESU D. &amp; GIROTTI O. 2010. - The Late Oligocene molluscan fauna from Otranto (Apulia, southern Italy): an example of alternating freshwater, lagoonal and emerged environments. Palaeontology 53: 137 - 174. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1475 - 4983.2009.00923. x" type="journal article" year="2010">Esu &amp; Girotti 2010</bibRefCitation>
) in being conical-ovate in shape, in having a less acute spire, a proportionally higher last whorl and wider and more elongate aperture. 
<emphasis box="[404,632,982,1008]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartmann" authorityYear="1821" box="[404,504,982,1008]" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Hydrobia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="8" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Hydrobia</taxonomicName>
dubuissonii
</emphasis>
from Oligocene deposits of 
<collectingCountry box="[306,378,1015,1041]" name="France" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">France</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[430,522,1014,1040]" name="Belgium" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">Belgium</collectingCountry>
(see above) differs from 
<emphasis box="[132,162,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">H.</emphasis>
(s.l.) 
<emphasis box="[227,291,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="7">ionica</emphasis>
n. sp. in having a conical-pyramidal shape, a more acute spire and a smaller and more ovate aperture.
</paragraph>
